From: Matthew Jackson <matthew@pq.io>
Subject: [PATCH 2/4] hw/misc/applesmc: add #KEY total-count key

On real Apple hardware the SMC firmware exposes a special key
#KEY whose value is a 4-byte big-endian count of all keys
(including #KEY itself). macOS uses this at boot as the upper
bound for its GET_KEY_BY_INDEX_CMD iteration: read #KEY, then
walk 0..count-1.

Without #KEY the macOS AppleSMC driver falls back to iterating
until it gets a BAD_INDEX reply. With patch 1 of this series in
place that fallback works, but boot-log noise and guest kernel
wake-ups are both reduced noticeably by providing the expected
key.

The count is computed by walking the data_def list at realize
time; the backing storage is function-static so the pointer
remains valid for the device lifetime.

Signed-off-by: Matthew Jackson <matthew@pq.io>
---
 hw/misc/applesmc.c | 21 +++++++++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 21 insertions(+)

--- a/hw/misc/applesmc.c
+++ b/hw/misc/applesmc.c
@@ -495,6 +495,27 @@
     applesmc_add_key(s, "NATJ", 1, "\0");
     applesmc_add_key(s, "MSSP", 1, "\0");
     applesmc_add_key(s, "MSSD", 1, "\0x3");
+
+    /*
+     * #KEY - Apple SMC convention for "total key count". macOS reads
+     * this at boot and iterates 0..count-1 via
+     * APPLESMC_GET_KEY_BY_INDEX_CMD. Without it, macOS falls back to
+     * iterating unbounded until it gets a BAD_INDEX reply; providing
+     * the key is cheap and avoids that fallback path. Count is
+     * computed by walking the list; the buffer is function-static so
+     * the pointer stays valid for the device's lifetime.
+     */
+    {
+        int count = 1;  /* include #KEY itself */
+        struct AppleSMCData *def;
+        QLIST_FOREACH(def, &s->data_def, node) count++;
+        static char numkey_buf[4];
+        numkey_buf[0] = (count >> 24) & 0xff;
+        numkey_buf[1] = (count >> 16) & 0xff;
+        numkey_buf[2] = (count >>  8) & 0xff;
+        numkey_buf[3] =  count        & 0xff;
+        applesmc_add_key(s, "#KEY", 4, numkey_buf);
+    }
 }
 
 static void applesmc_unrealize(DeviceState *dev)
--
